authors have only recently gained wide attention through the popularity of Marcia Muller, Sue Grafton, and Sara Paretsky.The essays in this collection grapple with a wide range of issues important to the female sleuth - the most important, perhaps, being the oft-heard challenge to her suitability for the job. Not surprisingly, gender issues are the main focus of all the essays; indeed, in detective novels with a woman protagonist, these issues are often right at the surface.Some of the papers see the female sleuth as an important force in popular fiction, but many also challenge the notion that the woman detective is a positive model for feminists. They argue that fictional female sleuths have lost the `otherness' that a feminine approach to the genre should encourage. Collectively, the essays also reveal the differences between British and American perspectives on the woman detective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAmerican fictionxWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish fictionxWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aFeminism and literature. 0aWomen detectivesvFiction. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Mystery & Detective.2bisacsh1 aAddison Roberts, Jeanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, SueEllen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristiansen, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGregory Klein, Kathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIrons, Glenwood, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIrons, Glenwood, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLeonardi, Susan J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMason, Bobbie Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r